It drives very well, nice and smooth.  The power operated top works perfectly.  The original bumpers, rear tail lamp bezels, gas cap, and emblems are starting to show their age.  The paint is very shiny and looks great going down the road.  If you look closely you could find some minor chips and scuffs here and there but nothing major.  Since this car has never been torn apart the all original body has terrific fitment.  Even the deck lid.  The trunk mat and spare tire cover appear to be original.  The tool bag pictured is newer.  The chassis is solid and shows well.  No rust or rot to be found.  Great sounding dual exhaust has a nice mellow tone so it is pleasant for top down driving.  No classic car turns heads like a red Mustang convertible!  Make it yours today and we will help you with financing, insurance, and delivery.

It"??s 1966 gasoline is only .32 cents a gallon. And this beautiful Signal Flare Red Ford Mustang Convertible rolls into showrooms for sale. Now with a completely rebuilt front end high compression pistons and a mild cam. This pony will definitely keep a smile on your face and wind in your hair with every drive. Hop inside and you"??ll be wrapped in deluxe pony interior. The 1966 Mustang debuted with moderate trim changes including a new grille side ornamentation wheel covers and gas cap. Fords new C-4 cruise-o-matic three-speed auto transmission became available for the 225 HP V8. The 289 HiPo K-code engine was also offered with a c4 transmission but it had stronger internals and can be identified by the outer casing of the servo which is marked with a C. The long duration solid-lifter camshaft that allowed the high revving 289 to make the horsepower it was known for was not friendly for a low stall speed automatic torque converter. The HiPo could be spotted very easily by the 1-inch-thick vibration damper (as compared to 1/2 inch on the 225-hp version) and the absence of a vacuum advance unit on the dual point distributor. With the valve covers off there is a large letter K stamped between the valve springs along with screw in studs (vs. a pressed in stud for other 289s) for the adjustable rocker arms. A large number of new paint and interior color options an AM/eight-track sound system and one of the first AM/FM mono automobile radios were also offered. It also removed the Falcon instrument cluster; the previously optional features including the round gauges and padded sun visors became standard equipment. The Mustang would be the best-selling convertible in 1966 with 72119 sold beating the number two Impala by almost 2:1To view the car in greater detail including an HD video and 100+ HD pictures please visit www.gatewayclassiccars.com or our Denver showroom. This '65 left the factory an original Raven Black convertible. Today it still sits covered in a fresh Raven Black repaint that was buffed and wet-sanded to a gorgeous shine. Black isn't one of those colors that you can hide a lot of flaws in and this one shows very well. It does appear that the quarters have been replaced at some point and the floors do have some patches in them, but both seem to have been done very well.

Powered by the iconic Ford 289ci V8, that has been painted in the legendary FoMoCo blue and equipped with flat black Mustang themed valve covers and air filter, this engine is a very reliable powerplant. Underneath the hood you'll also see a new starter, new flywheel, new coil, new distributor and new radiator. Bolted to the engine is a 4-speed manual transmission that sends power to a Ford 8.8. Stopping power comes courtesy of 4-wheel drum brakes.
If you are looking for your next springtime cruise vehicle, this is it! Don't miss out! It's not everyday you come across a factory raven black, 289, 4-speed convertible!
